---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base title="Multiple Audio Clips with ESP32 + PAM8403" description="Play multiple audio clips on an ESP32 with a PAM8403 amplifier. Three modes: button trigger, auto sequence, and linked playlist." fullWidth={true}>

<div class="pam-wrap">

  <!-- Sidebar -->
  <aside class="sidebar">
    <nav class="toc">
      <h3>Contents</h3>
      <ol>
        <li><a href="#before-you-start">Before You Start</a></li>
        <li><a href="#preparing-clips">Preparing Your Clips</a></li>
        <li><a href="#wiring">Wiring the Button</a></li>
        <li><a href="#button-mode">Button Mode</a></li>
        <li><a href="#auto-sequence">Auto Sequence</a></li>
        <li><a href="#linked-sequence">Linked Sequence</a></li>
      </ol>
    </nav>
  </aside>

  <!-- Main -->
  <main>

    <!-- Hero -->
    <div class="hero">
      <div class="category">Audio &bull; ESP32</div>
      <h1>Multiple Audio Clips<br>with ESP32 + PAM8403</h1>
      <div class="meta">
        <div class="meta-item"><strong>Modes:</strong> Button trigger, Auto sequence, Linked playlist</div>
        <div class="meta-item"><strong>Board:</strong> ESP32 Dev Board (38-pin)</div>
      </div>
      <div class="badge badge-untested">&#9888; Untested</div>
    </div>

    <!-- Before You Start -->
    <div class="section" id="before-you-start">
      <h2>Before You Start</h2>
      <p>This guide extends the <a href="/guides/pam8403-esp32-audio" class="term-link">PAM8403 audio guide</a>. You should already have the PAM8403 wired up and a single clip playing before continuing here.</p>
      <p style="margin-top:0.75rem;">This guide covers only what is new: preparing multiple clips, adding a button, and three sketch modes for triggering playback.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Preparing Clips -->
    <div class="section" id="preparing-clips">
      <h2>Preparing Your Clips</h2>
      <p>Run the ffmpeg and <code>wav_to_header.py</code> process from the PAM guide once per clip. Name each header file and variable uniquely:</p>
      <div class="code-wrap">
        <pre><code>python3 wav_to_header.py /tmp/clip1_8bit.wav clip1.h clip1
python3 wav_to_header.py /tmp/clip2_8bit.wav clip2.h clip2
python3 wav_to_header.py /tmp/clip3_8bit.wav clip3.h clip3</code></pre>
        <button class="copy-btn">Copy</button>
      </div>
      <p>Place all <code>.h</code> files in your <a href="/glossary/sketch-folder" class="term-link">sketch folder</a> alongside your <code>.ino</code> file.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Wiring -->
    <div class="section" id="wiring">
      <h2>Wiring the Button</h2>
      <p>For button mode, connect a tactile button between <strong>GPIO18</strong> and <strong>GND</strong>. No resistor needed - the sketch uses the ESP32's internal pull-up.</p>
      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Button pin</th><th>ESP32 pin</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>One leg</td><td>GPIO18</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Other leg</td><td>GND</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <div class="callout callout-tip">
        <strong>Auto sequence and linked sequence need no button.</strong>
        Skip this wiring if you are only using those modes.
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Button Mode -->
    <div class="section" id="button-mode">
      <h2>Button Mode</h2>
      <p>Each button press plays the next clip in the list. After the last clip it loops back to the first.</p>
      <div class="code-wrap">
        <pre><code>/*
 * We stand on the shoulders of giants when we build
 * with knowledge gained from others' efforts.
 * That doesn't make us giants. Be humble.
 * Create with care. Open source is the way.
 *
 * ESP32 + PAM8403 - Multiple Clips, Button Trigger
 * --------------------------------------------------
 * Cycles through audio clips on each button press.
 *
 * Open source - MIT Licence
 * Electronic Zoology - field notes from the garage
 * https://electroniczoology.com
 */

#include "clip1.h"
#include "clip2.h"
#include "clip3.h"

const int DAC_PIN     = 25;
const int SAMPLE_RATE = 8000;
const float VOLUME    = 0.8;
const int BUTTON_PIN  = 18;

struct Clip &#123;
  const uint8_t* data;
  uint32_t len;
&#125;;

const Clip clips[] = &#123;
  &#123; clip1_data, clip1_len &#125;,
  &#123; clip2_data, clip2_len &#125;,
  &#123; clip3_data, clip3_len &#125;,
&#125;;
const int CLIP_COUNT = sizeof(clips) / sizeof(clips[0]);

int currentClip = 0;

void playClip(const Clip&amp; c) &#123;
  uint32_t intervalUs = 1000000 / SAMPLE_RATE;
  for (uint32_t i = 0; i &lt; c.len; i++) &#123;
    uint8_t sample = pgm_read_byte(&amp;c.data[i]);
    int val = 128 + (int)((sample - 128) * VOLUME);
    dacWrite(DAC_PIN, constrain(val, 0, 255));
    delayMicroseconds(intervalUs);
  &#125;
  dacWrite(DAC_PIN, 128);
&#125;

void setup() &#123;
  pinMode(BUTTON_PIN, INPUT_PULLUP);
&#125;

void loop() &#123;
  if (digitalRead(BUTTON_PIN) == LOW) &#123;
    delay(30);
    if (digitalRead(BUTTON_PIN) == LOW) &#123;
      playClip(clips[currentClip]);
      currentClip = (currentClip + 1) % CLIP_COUNT;
      while (digitalRead(BUTTON_PIN) == LOW);
    &#125;
  &#125;
&#125;</code></pre>
        <button class="copy-btn">Copy</button>
      </div>
      <div class="callout callout-tip">
        <strong>Changing GPIO pin?</strong>
        Update <code>BUTTON_PIN</code> to any free GPIO. Avoid GPIO6-11 (used by flash) and GPIO34-39 (input only - no internal pull-up, so you would need an external 10k resistor to 3.3V).
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Auto Sequence -->
    <div class="section" id="auto-sequence">
      <h2>Auto Sequence</h2>
      <p>Plays every clip in order once on boot. No button needed.</p>
      <div class="code-wrap">
        <pre><code>/*
 * We stand on the shoulders of giants when we build
 * with knowledge gained from others' efforts.
 * That doesn't make us giants. Be humble.
 * Create with care. Open source is the way.
 *
 * ESP32 + PAM8403 - Multiple Clips, Auto Sequence
 * --------------------------------------------------
 * Plays all audio clips in order on boot.
 *
 * Open source - MIT Licence
 * Electronic Zoology - field notes from the garage
 * https://electroniczoology.com
 */

#include "clip1.h"
#include "clip2.h"
#include "clip3.h"

const int DAC_PIN     = 25;
const int SAMPLE_RATE = 8000;
const float VOLUME    = 0.8;

struct Clip &#123;
  const uint8_t* data;
  uint32_t len;
&#125;;

const Clip clips[] = &#123;
  &#123; clip1_data, clip1_len &#125;,
  &#123; clip2_data, clip2_len &#125;,
  &#123; clip3_data, clip3_len &#125;,
&#125;;
const int CLIP_COUNT = sizeof(clips) / sizeof(clips[0]);

void playClip(const Clip&amp; c) &#123;
  uint32_t intervalUs = 1000000 / SAMPLE_RATE;
  for (uint32_t i = 0; i &lt; c.len; i++) &#123;
    uint8_t sample = pgm_read_byte(&amp;c.data[i]);
    int val = 128 + (int)((sample - 128) * VOLUME);
    dacWrite(DAC_PIN, constrain(val, 0, 255));
    delayMicroseconds(intervalUs);
  &#125;
  dacWrite(DAC_PIN, 128);
&#125;

void setup() &#123;
  for (int i = 0; i &lt; CLIP_COUNT; i++) &#123;
    playClip(clips[i]);
  &#125;
&#125;

void loop() &#123; &#125;</code></pre>
        <button class="copy-btn">Copy</button>
      </div>
      <div class="callout callout-tip">
        <strong>Loop continuously?</strong>
        Move the <code>for</code> loop into <code>loop()</code> instead of <code>setup()</code> - the sequence repeats forever.
      </div>
      <div class="code-wrap">
        <pre><code>/*
 * We stand on the shoulders of giants when we build
 * with knowledge gained from others' efforts.
 * That doesn't make us giants. Be humble.
 * Create with care. Open source is the way.
 *
 * ESP32 + PAM8403 - Multiple Clips, Continuous Loop
 * --------------------------------------------------
 * Plays all audio clips in order, repeating forever.
 *
 * Open source - MIT Licence
 * Electronic Zoology - field notes from the garage
 * https://electroniczoology.com
 */

#include "clip1.h"
#include "clip2.h"
#include "clip3.h"

const int DAC_PIN     = 25;
const int SAMPLE_RATE = 8000;
const float VOLUME    = 0.8;

struct Clip &#123;
  const uint8_t* data;
  uint32_t len;
&#125;;

const Clip clips[] = &#123;
  &#123; clip1_data, clip1_len &#125;,
  &#123; clip2_data, clip2_len &#125;,
  &#123; clip3_data, clip3_len &#125;,
&#125;;
const int CLIP_COUNT = sizeof(clips) / sizeof(clips[0]);

void playClip(const Clip&amp; c) &#123;
  uint32_t intervalUs = 1000000 / SAMPLE_RATE;
  for (uint32_t i = 0; i &lt; c.len; i++) &#123;
    uint8_t sample = pgm_read_byte(&amp;c.data[i]);
    int val = 128 + (int)((sample - 128) * VOLUME);
    dacWrite(DAC_PIN, constrain(val, 0, 255));
    delayMicroseconds(intervalUs);
  &#125;
  dacWrite(DAC_PIN, 128);
&#125;

void setup() &#123; &#125;

void loop() &#123;
  for (int i = 0; i &lt; CLIP_COUNT; i++) &#123;
    playClip(clips[i]);
  &#125;
&#125;</code></pre>
        <button class="copy-btn">Copy</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Linked Sequence -->
    <div class="section" id="linked-sequence">
      <h2>Linked Sequence</h2>
      <p>Define a playlist array to control the exact order - repeat clips, skip some, or build a specific sequence.</p>
      <div class="code-wrap">
        <pre><code>/*
 * We stand on the shoulders of giants when we build
 * with knowledge gained from others' efforts.
 * That doesn't make us giants. Be humble.
 * Create with care. Open source is the way.
 *
 * ESP32 + PAM8403 - Multiple Clips, Linked Sequence
 * --------------------------------------------------
 * Plays audio clips in a user-defined playlist order.
 *
 * Open source - MIT Licence
 * Electronic Zoology - field notes from the garage
 * https://electroniczoology.com
 */

#include "clip1.h"
#include "clip2.h"
#include "clip3.h"

const int DAC_PIN     = 25;
const int SAMPLE_RATE = 8000;
const float VOLUME    = 0.8;

struct Clip &#123;
  const uint8_t* data;
  uint32_t len;
&#125;;

const Clip clips[] = &#123;
  &#123; clip1_data, clip1_len &#125;,
  &#123; clip2_data, clip2_len &#125;,
  &#123; clip3_data, clip3_len &#125;,
&#125;;

const int playlist[]   = &#123; 0, 1, 0, 2, 1 &#125;;
const int PLAYLIST_LEN = sizeof(playlist) / sizeof(playlist[0]);

void playClip(const Clip&amp; c) &#123;
  uint32_t intervalUs = 1000000 / SAMPLE_RATE;
  for (uint32_t i = 0; i &lt; c.len; i++) &#123;
    uint8_t sample = pgm_read_byte(&amp;c.data[i]);
    int val = 128 + (int)((sample - 128) * VOLUME);
    dacWrite(DAC_PIN, constrain(val, 0, 255));
    delayMicroseconds(intervalUs);
  &#125;
  dacWrite(DAC_PIN, 128);
&#125;

void setup() &#123;
  for (int i = 0; i &lt; PLAYLIST_LEN; i++) &#123;
    playClip(clips[playlist[i]]);
  &#125;
&#125;

void loop() &#123; &#125;</code></pre>
        <button class="copy-btn">Copy</button>
      </div>
      <div class="callout callout-why">
        <strong>How the index works</strong>
        <code>playlist[i]</code> is a number pointing to a position in the <code>clips[]</code> array. <code>0</code> = clip1, <code>1</code> = clip2, <code>2</code> = clip3. Repeat an index to play that clip more than once.
      </div>
    </div>

  </main>
</div>

</Base>

<style>
  .pam-wrap {
    max-width: 1140px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 2rem 1.5rem;
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 240px 1fr;
    gap: 2rem;
    align-items: start;
  }

  .sidebar {
    position: sticky;
    top: 76px;
  }
  .toc {
    background: #fff;
    border: 1px solid #e0e0e0;
    border-radius: 8px;
    padding: 1.25rem 1.5rem;
  }
  .toc h3 {
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 1px;
    color: #888;
    margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
  }
  .toc ol {
    list-style: none;
    counter-reset: toc;
    padding: 0;
    margin: 0;
  }
  .toc ol li {
    counter-increment: toc;
    margin-bottom: 0.4rem;
  }
  .toc ol li::before {
    content: counter(toc) ". ";
    color: var(--amber);
    font-weight: 700;
    font-size: 0.85rem;
  }
  .toc a {
    color: #444;
    text-decoration: none;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    transition: color 0.15s;
  }
  .toc a:hover { color: var(--amber); }
  .toc a.active { color: var(--amber); font-weight: 600; }

  main {
    background: #fff;
    border-radius: 8px;
    border: 1px solid #e0e0e0;
    padding: 2.5rem 3rem;
    min-width: 0;
  }

  .hero {
    background: linear-gradient(135deg, #1a1a2e 0%, #16213e 100%);
    color: #fff;
    border-radius: 8px;
    padding: 2rem 2.5rem;
    margin-bottom: 2.5rem;
  }
  .hero .category {
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 1.5px;
    background: var(--rainbow);
    -webkit-background-clip: text;
    -webkit-text-fill-color: transparent;
    background-clip: text;
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
  }
  .hero h1 {
    font-size: 1.8rem;
    font-weight: 800;
    line-height: 1.2;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
    color: #fff;
  }
  .hero .meta {
    display: flex;
    gap: 1.5rem;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
  }
  .hero .meta-item {
